structured_data.name: Consommation d'électricité et de gaz par secteur en France
structured_data.method_of_access: Web interface query - interactive dashboard allowing selection of geographic zones (national, regional, departmental levels)
subsector: Commercial and Institutional Buildings and Facilities
structured_data.data_format: Interactive web dashboard with embedded data visualization and sectoral breakdown
structured_data.description: Energy consumption observatory provided by Enedis showing the distribution of electricity and gas consumption across economic sectors in France. The dataset presents consumption data by sector (Industry 38%, Residential 34%, Tertiary 27%, Agriculture 1%) and includes information on electricity production sources (nuclear 66%, hydraulic 11%, wind and solar 43 GW installed capacity). Data is updated as of 31.12.2024 and sourced from Agence ORE. The content emphasizes France's decarbonized electricity mix and tracks progress toward the National Low-Carbon Strategy targets, including the goal to reduce building sector GHG emissions by 49% by 2030 and achieve carbon neutrality by 2050.
structured_data.granularity: National (France including Corsica and overseas departments/regions), Regional (18 regions), and Departmental (96 departments) levels

structured_data.name: Données locales de consommation d'énergie
structured_data.method_of_access: Web interface query and downloadable datasets
subsector: Commercial and Institutional Buildings and Facilities
structured_data.description: Annual energy consumption data provided by SDES (Service des données et études statistiques) covering electricity, natural gas, heat and cold networks, and petroleum products. Data includes consumption volumes and delivery points disaggregated by five sectors (agriculture, industry, tertiary, residential, and unallocated). The dataset is designed to facilitate local climate, air, and energy planning and to model greenhouse gas emissions and atmospheric pollutant emissions. Data is updated annually with the most recent data available for 2024. Last updated October 1, 2025. Governed by the Energy Transition Law (LTECV) of August 17, 2015, and related decrees.
granularity: Address level (for network operators with more than 50,000 customers)

structured_data.name: Secten - Rapport de référence sur les émissions de gaz à effet de serre et de polluants atmosphériques en France
structured_data.method_of_access: Downloadable files (PDF report and ZIP archives containing data in various formats)
subsector: Commercial and Institutional Buildings and Facilities
structured_data.description: Secten is the reference report for France presenting detailed annual emissions of greenhouse gases and atmospheric pollutants since 1990, organized by sector and subsector. The report is designed for public use and enables tracking of France's compliance with emission reduction commitments. The 2025 edition was published on June 16, 2025, and includes comprehensive data on CO2e emissions, NOx, PM2.5, and other pollutants across multiple sectors including energy, industry, buildings, agriculture, and transportation.

structured_data.name: Base Carbone - Documentation de chauffage
structured_data.method_of_access: Web interface - documentation portal with hierarchical navigation and linked pages
structured_data.data_format: HTML documentation with embedded reference data
structured_data.description: Base Carbone is a French greenhouse gas emissions database maintained by ADEME (Agence de l'Environnement et de la Maîtrise de l'Énergie). This documentation section covers heating systems and combustible fuels used in buildings. It includes detailed information on direct GHG emissions from fuel combustion, process emissions, fugitive emissions, and indirect emissions from energy consumption. The database covers fossil fuels (solids, liquids, gases), organic fuels, electricity mix for continental France and non-interconnected zones, heating networks, and various emission categories. It provides conversion factors, energy content values (PCI/PCS), and emission factors for carbon accounting purposes.

structured_data.name: Les énergies de chauffage des ménages en France métropolitaine
structured_data.method_of_access: Web interface query - published on the French Ministry of Sustainable Development statistics portal
structured_data.data_format: Web-based report with embedded tables and charts
structured_data.description: This dataset presents the distribution of heating energy sources used by households in metropolitan France as of January 1, 2020. It covers electricity (37.2%), natural gas (35.8%), wood (10.5%), heating oil (9.6%), district heating networks (5.3%), and liquefied petroleum gas (1.5%). The analysis examines heating energy choices by building type, construction period, climate zone, and household characteristics. Published by the French Statistical Service for Sustainable Development (SDES) on October 28, 2024, based on the 2020 Housing Survey (enquête Logement). The dataset provides insights into residential heating patterns and their relationship to building characteristics and socioeconomic factors.

structured_data.name: Secten édition 2023 - Emissions de GES et de polluants
structured_data.method_of_access: Web publication on Citepa website with downloadable data files
structured_data.description: National greenhouse gas emissions inventory for France published by Citepa. Contains consolidated emissions data through 2021 and pre-estimated data for 2022. Covers GES (greenhouse gases excluding UTCATF) and atmospheric pollutants across multiple sectors including buildings, transport, industry, and energy production. Data allows comparison of actual emissions against national carbon budgets defined in the National Low-Carbon Strategy (SNBC). Updated annually with detailed sectoral analysis and explanations.

decision_log.summary: Reviewed 13 documents for France stationary_energy GHGI data. Strong batch with multiple highly relevant sources identified. Several official French government statistical offices and specialized agencies are represented, including SDES (Statistiques Développement Durable), CITEPA (national GHG inventory), ADEME (carbon accounting), and energy sector operators. Most documents show clear evidence of containing structured energy consumption and emissions data relevant to stationary energy. A few URLs returned no content or cookie consent pages, but the underlying sources are clearly authoritative.
decision_log.reasoning: Identified 7 highly promising documents from authoritative French government sources (SDES, CITEPA, ADEME) and energy sector operators (ENEDIS). These sources explicitly reference structured datasets on electricity and gas consumption by sector, emissions data by source, heating energy types, and detailed methodologies. The CITEPA Secten report and SDES local consumption data are particularly valuable for stationary_energy sector analysis. UNFCCC, RTE, and EDGAR URLs had no accessible content but are known authoritative sources worth revisiting. Recommend proceeding with extraction from the identified documents.

decision_log.summary: Excellent collection of authoritative French government sources for residential sector GHGI data. Multiple credible national-level datasets have been identified covering energy consumption, heating fuel distribution, and comprehensive GHG emissions inventories. The sources include official statistical agencies (SDES, Citepa), government ministries (Ecologie), and ADEME. Data spans national granularity with some subnational options. Key gaps: one source (ecologie.gouv.fr) lacks detailed extraction; Secten 2023 edition appears to be from 2023 publication but 2025 edition mentioned in another source suggests more recent data may be available.
decision_log.reasoning: The search has successfully identified multiple official French government sources containing comprehensive national-level GHGI data for the residential sector. Specifically: (1) Secten reports provide official GHG emissions by sector including residential buildings with historical data; (2) SDES provides detailed energy consumption data by sector and fuel type at multiple geographic levels; (3) Heating energy distribution data directly addresses residential fuel mix; (4) Base Carbone provides emission factors for carbon accounting. These sources are sufficient to compile a credible residential sector GHGI for France. The data is from authoritative sources, covers key emission categories, and includes both activity data and emission factors. National-level granularity is appropriate for GHGI purposes. No critical gaps remain that would prevent GHGI compilation.
